The '501 Queen' is an east-west streetcar route in Toronto, Ontario, Canada,
operated by the Toronto Transit Commission (TTC). {{cite news
| url = http://news.nationalpost.com/2012/03/24/riding-the-501-the-longest-streetcar-
| route-in-north-america/ title = Riding the 501: The longest streetcar route in
| North America publisher = National Post author = Vanessa Farquharson date =
| 2012-03-24 archivedate = 2013-02-24 archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/q-
| uery?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnews.nationalpost.com%2F2012%2F03%2F24%2Friding-the-501-
| the-longest-streetcar-route-in-north-america%2F&date=2013-02-24 deadurl = No
| quote = With nearly 25 kilometres of track, the 501 Queen is the longest
| streetcar route operating in North America.
}}  At , it is the TTC's longest surface route, the longest streetcar
route operating in North America and one of the longest streetcar routes
operating in the world. {{cite news
| url = http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/1405066861.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS-
| =ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+29%2C+2007&author=Christopher+Hume&pub=Toronto+-
| Star&desc=It%27s+not+too+good+if+you%27re+in+a+hurry%2C+but+the+501+does+give-
| +a+wonderful+look+at+city%27s+many+faces&pqatl=google title = It's not too
| good if you're in a hurry, but the 501 does give a wonderful look at city's
| many faces publisher = Toronto Star author = Christopher Hume date = 2007-12-
| 29 page = A.3 accessdate = 2013-02-24 quote = Torontonians who ride it daily
| might not be impressed, butNational Geographic has named the Queen streetcar,
| the 501, one of the top 10 trolley routes in the world. The honour is included
| in a new book, Journeys of a Lifetime 500 of the World's Greatest Trips.
}}  It stretches from Long Branch Loop (just west of Browns Line, adjacent
to Long Branch GO Station) in the west to Neville Park Loop (just west of
Victoria Park Avenue) in the east, running on Lake Shore Boulevard, in a
reserved right-of-way at the median of The Queensway, and on Queen Street. The
route was first instituted in the mid-to-late-19th century by private operators
as a horse-drawn line, was later electrified, and was assumed by the TTC upon
its creation in 1921. Service is provided 24 hours a day, though the route
number changes to '301 Queen' late at night.

The 501 Queen is one of the routes regularly operated with the TTC's double-
length ALRVs. It runs with a combined service of five minutes during rush
hour, four to ten at other times, and 10 to 30 overnight from approximately
1:00 a.m. until 5:00 a.m. The route is split into two branches, one running
from Neville Park to Humber Loop on the Queensway, and the other running all
the way to Long Branch. Every other streetcar is scheduled to go to Long
Branch. The route interchanges with the Yonge-University-Spadina subway line
at Queen and Osgoode stations.
